  <li id="comment-21064" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Maya in Eugene</cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=702#comment-21064"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2010-10-27T14:38:19-04:00">Wednesday, October 27, 2010 at 2:38 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Great recipe&#8230; my family is from Catalonia and the only thing different about this recipe and my Tia Carmen&#39;s is a bit of crusty bread &#8211; I use day-old homemade bread.  Try adding a little bread to the whirring blender and it&#39;ll be even creamier and makes the color even more golden.  That one detail is enough to make a native Spaniard feel close to home!  Also, while we think of tomatoes first when we think of this cold soup, remember that gazpacho is a garlic-based &#8220;soup,&#8221; (some parts of Spain make it white with no tomatoes!) so the better the garlic, the better the soup.  I use rocambole from my garden.  When it&#39;s freshly picked (even within a few weeks hanging) a little goes a looooong way!  So happy you found a way to connect to this fabulous concoction.  </p>
<p>Oh &#8211; and I love your blog.  I&#39;ve tried so many recipes and have not found one dud yet!</p>
    </div>

